Table 4 lists the activation energy of CMR drying. It ranged from 16.93 to 30.39 kJ/mol. WS had the largest value of E due to its lumpy structure, which hindered the internal moisture diffusion (Fig. S3). The drying activation energy of diverse feedstocks varied greatly. The activation energy of Angelica was 68.82 and 29.60 kJ/mol at 50 ~ 70 ℃ by the temperature-controlled blast drying and infrared drying, respectively [73]. Falade et al. observed that the drying activation energy of yam slices with different thicknesses and pretreatment methods varied greatly [74]. For yam slices, potato slices, and carrots, it was within the range of 20 ~ 30 kJ/mol [35]. The fresh herb gastrodia elata had the drying activation energy of 34.16 kJ/mol, which was close to that of Codonopsis and Poria Cocos [31]. It indicated that CMR samples could dried easily after decoction.Table 4
